{"type":"message","id":"b8de08ce","parentId":"5da17d78","timestamp":"2026-02-26T21:39:32.062Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Clarifying macOS Calendar Skill**\n\nI need to answer a question about credential handling in the macOS Calendar skill. According to the SKILL.md, it uses AppleScript and interacts directly with Calendar.app without needing separate credentials. The user must enable accessibility and calendar access permissions on their macOS. If running remotely, it may need to execute on the host machine. For iCloud users, any calendar login would occur through Calendar.app itself, so there's no direct handling in the skill. I'll also offer to run a test afterward.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"Short answer: there isn’t a separate credentials provisioning step for macos-calendar.\n\nWhat it uses and what you need to set up:\n- It talks to macOS Calendar.app via AppleScript (osascript) and some Python for JSON parsing.\n- There are no API keys or login credentials to supply to the skill itself.\n- Access control you need to handle on the Mac:\n  - The script needs permission to control Calendar apps (Automation permissions). You may be prompted the first time.\n  - Calendar access in System Settings > Privacy & Security > Calendars (and possibly Accessibility and Automation) to allow the script to read/write events.\n  - If you’re using iCloud calendars, Calendar.app will use the account configured in Calendar.app; no hard credentials in the skill.\n\nIf you want, I can run a quick test to list calendars (which will prompt for permission if needed) and confirm access."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openrouter/auto","usage":{"input":1898,"output":593,"cacheRead":10624,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":13115,"cost":{"input":-1898,"output":-593,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":-2491}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1772141967334}}
