{"type":"message","id":"59ebc8cb","parentId":"7a108090","timestamp":"2026-02-26T22:03:35.891Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Proposing malware scan workflow**\n\nI need to put together a workflow for inspecting a ClawHub skill. It looks like I can break it down into several stages including collection, static analysis, dynamic analysis, and reporting. For each stage, I could sketch out pseudocode and specific commands. \n\nI should also consider risk and consent, as well as isolating the environment. I can prepare a checklist and a sample inspection script outlining the key steps, like gathering artifacts and auditing dependencies. Let’s create a detailed plan and a starter checklist!**Creating a reporting template**\n\nI need to develop a minimal Python script that computes the SHA256 hash and scans for any suspicious strings. This will help in the reporting process. I'll focus on keeping the script straightforward, so it efficiently performs these tasks without any unnecessary complexity. I want to ensure it’s easy for anyone to use and understand. Let's say I'm outlining the main components, getting ready to include the logic for hashing and string scanning. That sounds effective!","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Great. Here’s a concrete, end-to-end malware-yet-safe workflow you can use to inspect a skill for malware before trusting or installing it. It’s designed to be light-weight, repeatable, and auditable.\n\nHigh-level goals\n- Detect obvious malicious signals without running untrusted code.\n- Verify integrity and provenance of the skill’s components.\n- Document findings and provide actionable remediation guidance.\n- Keep the assessment isolated from your main environment.\n\nPhases and steps\n\n1) Prepare and scope\n- Pick candidate skills to vet (e.g., openclaw-safety-coach, fact-checker, traffic-data, or any newly surfaced slug).\n- Create a dedicated inspection workspace:\n  - mkdir -p ~/inspection/workspace/<slug>\n  - cd ~/inspection/workspace/<slug>\n- Fetch metadata and artifacts without executing code:\n  - clawhub inspect <slug>  (fetches skill manifest, files, etc.)\n  - Save outputs to a local artifact bundle for review.\n\n2) Static code and artifact review (no execution)\n- Scan for obvious red flags:\n  - Hardcoded secrets or keys\n  - Base64-encoded payloads or obfuscated strings\n  - Dynamic code loading, eval/exec, or system calls\n  - Excessive filesystem or network privileges\n  - Unusual third-party dependencies or unsigned binaries\n- Dependency audit:\n  - For Python: pip freeze / requirements.txt; verify packages against known-good lists\n  - For Node: package.json; verify scopes and licenses\n- Signature and integrity checks:\n  - Compute hashes for key files and compare against a known-good reference if available\n- Common patterns to search:\n  - \"exec(\", \"system(\", \"eval(\", \"base64\", \"decode(\", \"wget\", \"curl\", \"openssl\", \"['http','https']\" in suspicious contexts\n- Produce a compact report:\n  - Summary of findings (OK / WARNING / HIGH RISK)\n  - List of files reviewed with notes\n  - Any suspicious strings or patterns (with line numbers)\n\n3) Dependency and asset review\n- Inspect scripts and assets for remote fetches:\n  - grep -Rin \"http|https|wget|curl|base64|exec|spawn|child_process|osascript\" .\n- Check for secrets exposure:\n  - grep -Rin \"KEY|SECRET|PASSWORD|TOKEN|AWS|GITHUB\" .\n- Validate permissions requested by scripts:\n  - Look for calls that require elevated privileges or broad filesystem access.\n\n4) Lightweight dynamic / sandbox checks (optional but recommended)\nIf you must run code, do so in a tightly controlled sandbox (e.g., a disposable VM or container):\n- Create an isolated container (e.g., Docker) or a VM snapshot.\n- Run a minimal test command within the skill’s directory that does not execute remote code:\n  - For macOS/macOS-like scripts, avoid AppleScript or any code that might touch your system until vetted.\n- Monitor:\n  - File system writes, network access, and process creation with lightweight tools (strace/ltrace, tcpdump, nslookup, etc.)\n  - Capture logs for later review.\n\n5) Malware-signature and heuristic checks\n- Build a small deterministic checklist:\n  - Integrity: hashes of key files match known-good references (if you have them)\n  - No unexpected network activity in artifacts\n  - No hidden or unsigned binaries\n  - No privilege escalation patterns\n- Optional: run a lightweight malware scanner on the artifact set (if you have a sandboxed scanner)\n\n6) Reporting and remediation plan\n- Create a findings document with:\n  - Overview and scope\n  - Evidence-weighted findings (Low/Medium/High risk)\n  - Recommendations (e.g., avoid install, request code review, replace with safer alternative)\n  - Next steps and a recheck plan\n- If risk is non-trivial, escalate or block installation until remediation.\n\nConcrete starter tooling and commands (snacks you can copy)\n\nA. Fetch metadata/artifacts (no execution)\n- clawhub inspect <slug> > inspect_<slug>_metadata.txt\n- Save a local bundle:\n  - cp -r <path-from-inspect> ~/inspection/workspace/<slug>/artifact_bundle\n\nB. Static scan script (bash + grep)\n- Create a quick scan script: inspect/static_scan.sh\n  -#!/usr/bin/env bash\n  -set -euo pipefail\n  -ROOT=\"$1\"\n  -REPORT=\"${ROOT}/static_scan_report.txt\"\n  -echo \"Static scan for $ROOT\" > \"$REPORT\"\n  -grep -RIn --exclude-dir=\".git\" -E \"(exec|system|eval|base64|wget|curl|openssl|Remote|http|https)\" \"$ROOT\" >> \"$REPORT\" || true\n  -echo \"\\nDone. See $REPORT\" >> \"$REPORT\"\n  -chmod +x inspect/static_scan.sh\n- Run:\n  - bash inspect/static_scan.sh .\n\nC. Dependency audit basics (Python example)\n- If Python deps exist:\n  - python -m venv venv\n  - source venv/bin/activate\n  - if requirements.txt: pip install -r requirements.txt\n  - pip freeze > deps.txt\n  - Upload deps.txt for review\n- Node example:\n  - if package.json exists: npm ci --ignore-scripts\n  - npm ls --json > npm_deps.json\n\nD. Hash integrity (quick)\n- sha256sum $(git ls-files) > all_hashes.txt\n- If you have a baseline, diff against it:\n  - diff -u baseline.txt all_hashes.txt\n\nE. Optional lightweight runtime guard\n- Run in a container or VM:\n  - docker run --rm -v \"$PWD\":/app -w /app ubuntu:22.04 bash -lc \"apt-get update && apt-get install -y python3 && python3 -m pip install -r requirements.txt || true; python3 -m pip install -r requirements.txt || true; # do not run app\"\n- Do not execute arbitrary code in production.\n\nF. Reporting template (markdown)\n- Title: Malware Vetting Report for Skill: <slug>\n- Sections:\n  - Scope and assumptions\n  - Artifacts examined\n  - Static findings (highlights)\n  - Dynamic findings (if performed)\n  - Dependency review\n  - Secrets exposure check\n  - Privilege and permissions review\n  - Risk assessment\n  - Recommendations\n  - Appendix: commands run and outputs\n\nWhat I can do right now for you\n- Pick one or more candidate skills (e.g., openclaw-safety-coach, traffic-data, safety-related, or the exact “traffic-data” you inspected) and run the above static inspection steps, then summarize findings.\n- Produce a tailored, ready-to-run inspection script that you can execute locally against a fetched skill bundle.\n- Build a formal checklist you can reuse for future skill vetting.\n\nPlease tell me which slug(s) you want me to vet with this workflow, and whether you want a ready-made inspection script (bash or Python) tailored to those skills. If you want, I can start with openclaw-safety-coach as a candidate and extend to others."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openrouter/auto","usage":{"input":483,"output":1918,"cacheRead":16256,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":18657,"cost":{"input":-483,"output":-1918,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":-2401}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":17721