{"type":"message","id":"b5516cb1","parentId":"8eb96067","timestamp":"2026-02-26T22:05:06.581Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Creating a skills template**\n\nI'm planning to provide a template named SKILLS.md with specific sections and commands. My idea is to respond with the content of the template and offer to write it to a file. Since there's no tool call, I'll keep it straightforward by proposing the content first and asking for confirmation to write it. I don't want to overstep, so I’ll also include an outline and example sections in my response. Let's get started on that!","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] I can create a comprehensive skills.md that encodes the malware-vetting workflow as a repeatable skill guide. Below is a ready-to-use draft you can copy into a file like SKILLS.md (or I can write it to /home/ec2-user/.openclaw/workspace/skills/malware-vet/SKILLS.md if you want me to).\n\nMalware Vetting Skill - SKILLS.md\n\nOverview\n- Purpose: Provide a repeatable, auditable workflow to inspect a ClawHub skill for malware before trusting or installing it.\n- Scope: Static analysis of artifacts, provenance checks, lightweight dynamic checks in a sandbox, and a formal findings report.\n- When to use: Before installing any third-party skill, especially for high-risk surfaces or sensitive environments.\n\nHigh-level workflow (phases)\n1) Preparation and scoping\n   - Select candidate skills to vet (e.g., traffic-data, openclaw-safety-coach, a new skill surfaced by explore).\n   - Create an isolated inspection workspace.\n   - Gather metadata and artifacts without executing code:\n     - clawhub inspect <slug>  (fetch manifest and files)\n     - Archive outputs to a local bundle for review\n\n2) Static code and artifact review (no execution)\n   - Red flags to look for:\n     - Hardcoded secrets or keys\n     - Base64-encoded payloads or obfuscation\n     - Dynamic code loading, eval/exec, system calls\n     - Excessive or broad permissions\n     - Unusual third-party dependencies or unsigned binaries\n   - Dependency audit basics:\n     - Python: check requirements.txt / pip freeze\n     - Node: check package.json / licenses\n   - Integrity checks:\n     - Compute hashes of key files; compare to known-good references if available\n   - Output: A concise report with findings and file-level notes\n\n3) Dependency and asset review\n   - Inspect scripts/assets for remote fetches or external payloads\n   - Check for exposure of secrets (SEARCH for KEY, SECRET, TOKEN, etc.)\n   - Validate the permissions requested by scripts\n\n4) Lightweight dynamic checks (optional but recommended)\n   - Run in a controlled sandbox (VM or container) if you must execute:\n     - Avoid running untrusted code on host\n     - Monitor for unexpected file writes, network calls, or process spawning\n   - Capture and store evidence for later review\n\n5) Malware-signature and heuristic checks\n   - Build a minimal risk checklist:\n     - Integrity of key files\n     - Absence of suspicious network activity in artifacts\n     - No hidden or unsigned binaries\n     - No privilege-escalation patterns\n   - Optional: run a lightweight scanner in a sandbox\n\n6) Reporting and remediation plan\n   - Produce a Findings Report:\n     - Scope, artifacts inspected, evidence, risk rating\n     - Clear remediation options (avoid install, request code review, replace with safer alternative)\n     - Next steps and recheck plan\n   - Archive artifacts and the report for audit\n\nConcrete starter tooling and commands (snacks you can copy)\n- Fetch metadata/artifacts (no execution)\n  clawhub inspect <slug> > inspect_<slug>_metadata.txt\n- Static scan (bash glimpse)\n  mkdir -p ~/inspection/workspace/<slug>\n  cat inspect_<slug>_metadata.txt | tee -a ~/inspection/workspace/<slug>/report.txt\n  # Quick grep for red flags\n  grep -RIn --exclude-dir=\".git\" -E \"(exec|system|eval|base64|wget|curl|openssl|Remote|http|https)\" <slug-file-path> >> ~/inspection/workspace/<slug>/report.txt\n\n- Dependency review (example paths)\n  - Python: if requirements.txt exists, inspect with pip and record\n  - Node: if package.json exists, npm ci && npm ls --json\n\n- Hashing (integrity)\n  sha256sum <files> > integrity.md\n\n- Reporting template (markdown)\n  - Title: Malware Vetting Report for Skill: <slug>\n  - Sections: Scope, Artifacts, Static Findings, Dynamic Findings (if any), Dependency Review, Secrets Exposure, Permissions, Risk, Recommendations, Appendix (commands and outputs)\n\nReady-to-use file layout\n- Create path: /home/ec2-user/.openclaw/workspace/skills/malware-vet/\n- File: /home/ec2-user/.openclaw/workspace/skills/malware-vet/SKILLS.md\n\nWhat I can do next\n- Write this draft as an actual SKILLS.md file now.\n- Customize with:\n  - Your preferred slug(s) for vetting\n  - A ready-made static_scan.sh script tailored to your environment\n  - A compact, reproducible checklist and a small Python/Bash harness for running the checks\n- Provide a runnable example using a specific candidate slug (e.g., openclaw-safety-coach or traffic-data) to illustrate the exact commands and report format.\n\nTell me:\n- Do you want me to create/write SKILLS.md now at the path above?\n- Any preferred slug(s) you want included in the first pass?\n- Should I attach a minimal static_scan.sh and a sample findings.md to accompany it?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openrouter/auto","usage":{"input":1626,"output":1619,"cacheRead":16640,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":19885,"cost":{"input":-1626,"output":-1619,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":-3245}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1772143495233}}
